1
00:05:46,158 --> 00:05:48,700
<i>London.</i>

2
00:06:09,492 --> 00:06:11,742
<i>Heil Hitler!</i>

3
00:06:15,283 --> 00:06:17,283
<i>Doktor.</i>

4
00:07:01,742 --> 00:07:04,408
<i>Captain Alan Thorndike, Engländer.</i>

5
00:07:04,492 --> 00:07:08,700
<i>T- H-O-R-N-D-I-K-E.</i>

6
00:07:08,700 --> 00:07:10,742
<i>K- E.</i>

7
00:07:35,367 --> 00:07:39,242
<i>Langsam. Langsam.</i>

8
00:07:55,575 --> 00:07:57,575
Please be seated, Captain Thorndike.

9
00:08:02,117 --> 00:08:04,492
Thank you.

10
00:08:12,575 --> 00:08:14,617
Have a cigarette.

11
00:08:16,033 --> 00:08:18,325
Thank you.

12
00:08:18,408 --> 00:08:22,450
You know, if you just walked up to
this house in a normal way, instead of, uh-

13
00:08:24,033 --> 00:08:27,700
you would've been invited
to lunch by our führer.

14
00:08:27,742 --> 00:08:31,075
I've anticipated the pleasure
of meeting you for years.

15
00:08:32,575 --> 00:08:34,492
I'm afraid I don't know-

16
00:08:34,575 --> 00:08:37,825
Like you, my dear Thorndike,
I had but one passion in life...

17
00:08:37,908 --> 00:08:40,117
and that is the hunting of big game.

18
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:42,742
I'm convinced that I would've
become more famous even than yourself...

19
00:08:42,783 --> 00:08:45,908
if I hadn't renounced it
in favor of politics.

20
00:08:45,992 --> 00:08:47,908
Politics?

21
00:08:47,992 --> 00:08:51,533
Yes, I, uh, find it a more exciting
field of action-

22
00:08:51,617 --> 00:08:54,033
my branch of it.

23
00:08:54,117 --> 00:08:56,742
You're surprised that
I know your name so well.

24
00:08:56,825 --> 00:09:00,950
I was in Nairobi on my own safari the year
that all Kenya rang with your exploits.

25
00:09:01,033 --> 00:09:04,033
So you see, it's quite natural that
I should know who you are.

26
00:09:04,075 --> 00:09:06,658
Yes.

27
00:09:06,700 --> 00:09:10,117
And also you've taken, uh...

28
00:09:10,158 --> 00:09:12,117
my passport.

29
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:15,408
Nonetheless, my dear Thorndike,
I should've recognized you on sight-

30
00:09:15,450 --> 00:09:18,117
a man whose brother was a guest
in this house only last September.

31
00:09:18,158 --> 00:09:20,408
So you know my brother?

32
00:09:20,492 --> 00:09:23,867
When Lord Risborough was sent here by
your prime minister on a mission of appeasement.

33
00:09:26,492 --> 00:09:28,533
I found him a credulous simpleton.

34
00:09:31,367 --> 00:09:34,742
Do you know, Thorndike, that this is
the most closely guarded house in the world?

35
00:09:35,867 --> 00:09:37,742
Rather.

36
00:09:37,825 --> 00:09:39,867
I would've staked my life
that no living thing...

37
00:09:39,908 --> 00:09:43,117
could've entered this area
without being seen.

38
00:09:43,200 --> 00:09:45,533
But then, of course,
we didn't count upon a creature...

39
00:09:45,617 --> 00:09:47,825
that has learned to stalk
the most cunning animal...

40
00:09:47,908 --> 00:09:49,950
that can catch scents
upon the Wind...

41
00:09:49,992 --> 00:09:54,200
that has mastered the trick of moving
through a forest as if he were transparent.

42
00:09:54,283 --> 00:09:57,742
Look out there.
For 500 yards, not a tree, not a shrub.

43
00:09:57,825 --> 00:10:02,283
A man running towards this house would
be cut down before he'd taken five steps.

44
00:10:03,908 --> 00:10:06,533
And yet on that ledge above...

45
00:10:06,617 --> 00:10:08,700
was a man with a precision rifle...

46
00:10:08,783 --> 00:10:12,700
and a High degree of intelligence
and skill that is required to use it.

47
00:10:14,117 --> 00:10:17,408
Your judgment of distance
is uncanny, Thorndike.

48
00:10:17,492 --> 00:10:21,950
The sights were set at 550 yards,
only 10 feet short of the exact range.

49
00:10:21,992 --> 00:10:24,033
I checked it.

50
00:10:28,325 --> 00:10:33,617
Obviously, my dear Thorndike,
such a man cannot be allowed to live.

51
00:10:34,783 --> 00:10:37,908
Surely you don't think
I'm an assassin.

52
00:10:37,992 --> 00:10:40,283
You were stopped
before you could shoot.

53
00:10:40,367 --> 00:10:42,825
But I could have easily.

54
00:10:42,908 --> 00:10:46,242
<i>Good heavens, man,
I never Intended to shoot.</i>

55
00:10:46,325 --> 00:10:49,283
I merely wanted to find out
if it were possible.

56
00:10:49,367 --> 00:10:52,158
That was the excitement of it-
the danger, the fun.

57
00:10:52,242 --> 00:10:55,408
It was that fellow jumping me
that made my gun go off.

58
00:10:55,450 --> 00:10:57,492
You disappoint me, Thorndike.

59
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:01,450
I daresay I have been a bit thick...

60
00:11:01,533 --> 00:11:04,950
but, well, from the way you talked
about hunting and all that...

61
00:11:05,033 --> 00:11:07,700
I assumed you knew
it was a sporting stalk.

62
00:11:07,742 --> 00:11:09,950
A what?

63
00:11:09,992 --> 00:11:14,658
A sporting stalk. Stalking the game
you're after for the fun of it- not to kill.

64
00:11:16,033 --> 00:11:18,033
Oh, I'm not begging off
from any consequences...

65
00:11:18,117 --> 00:11:21,783
but you will permit me to doubt
your claims as a hunter of big game...

66
00:11:21,825 --> 00:11:25,867
if you fail to understand the fascination
for a man who's hunted all commoner game...

67
00:11:25,950 --> 00:11:28,075
of hunting the biggest game
on Earth.

68
00:11:28,158 --> 00:11:30,325
That's it. Precisely.

69
00:11:30,408 --> 00:11:33,325
The most dangerous
of all animals- man.

70
00:11:33,367 --> 00:11:37,575
But you don't kill.
The sport is in the chase, not the kill.

71
00:11:37,658 --> 00:11:40,492
I don't kill any longer,
not even small game.

72
00:11:40,575 --> 00:11:43,283
<i>I know what I can do with a rifle.</i>

73
00:11:43,367 --> 00:11:47,617
If I can stalk an animal and get within range,
the rest is a mathematical certainty.

74
00:11:47,700 --> 00:11:50,533
And that's sheer cruelty,
and I don't like cruelty.

75
00:11:50,617 --> 00:11:54,283
The real fun is matching my wits
against the instinct of an animal...

76
00:11:54,325 --> 00:11:56,700
<i>that Isn't going to let me
get near enough to shoot.</i>

77
00:11:56,700 --> 00:11:59,533
Your conversation
fascinates me, Thorndike.

78
00:11:59,617 --> 00:12:03,908
But this softness in your nature with
regard to the ultimate purpose of firearms...

79
00:12:03,992 --> 00:12:08,867
betrays the weakness, the decadence,
not only of yourself but of your entire race.

80
00:12:08,950 --> 00:12:11,908
Yes, you're symbolic
of the English race.

81
00:12:11,992 --> 00:12:13,908
I'm beginning to think that
you're symbolic of yours.

82
00:12:13,992 --> 00:12:16,658
We Nazis are finding a new life,
a new vitality for our people...

83
00:12:16,700 --> 00:12:18,658
by returning to
the primitive virtues.

84
00:12:18,700 --> 00:12:20,867
Such as going back
to the barbarism of decapitation?

85
00:12:20,950 --> 00:12:24,158
We do not hesitate to destroy
in order to create a new world.

86
00:12:24,242 --> 00:12:26,367
God help it.
I'm sorry for you.

87
00:12:26,450 --> 00:12:29,575
And I for you, Thorndike-
you and your world.

88
00:12:34,242 --> 00:12:36,575
<i>- Heil Hitler!
- Heil Hitler!</i>

89
00:12:52,492 --> 00:12:54,450
<i>Heil Hitler!</i>

90
00:13:08,367 --> 00:13:10,367
You will leave this country
a free man.

91
00:13:10,450 --> 00:13:13,283
You can return to your position and
friends in spite of what you've done.

92
00:13:13,367 --> 00:13:16,367
- On what condition?
- Your name signed to this.

93
00:13:16,408 --> 00:13:20,158
Later, it will be witnessed by the chief
of secret police and other officials.

94
00:13:20,242 --> 00:13:23,242
What is it? A suicide note?

95
00:13:26,658 --> 00:13:30,200
It is a confession that on
this 29th day of July, 1939...

96
00:13:30,283 --> 00:13:32,450
you have attempted to
assassinate our führer...

97
00:13:32,533 --> 00:13:36,700
and that you have undertaken this crime
with the approval of your government.

98
00:13:38,950 --> 00:13:40,908
I what?

99
00:13:40,992 --> 00:13:43,658
That you have acted
as an assassin for the British government.

100
00:13:43,700 --> 00:13:47,908
I can't believe you're serious.
Do you expect me to sign a lie?

101
00:13:47,992 --> 00:13:50,242
- You still insist you had no intention to shoot?
- Of course.

102
00:13:50,325 --> 00:13:52,242
I told you it was a sporting stalk.

103
00:13:52,325 --> 00:13:55,992
- Then why didn't you leave your rifle behind?
- Uh-

104
00:13:56,075 --> 00:13:58,575
I've asked myself that.

105
00:13:58,658 --> 00:14:01,908
And I think the answer is that-

106
00:14:01,992 --> 00:14:05,575
that it wouldn't have been sporting,
it wouldn't have been playing the game.

107
00:14:05,658 --> 00:14:09,992
Nothing betrays the hypocrisy of the English
more than their use of playing the game. "

108
00:14:10,075 --> 00:14:12,742
- One plays a game to win, Thorndike.
- Nonsense.

109
00:14:12,825 --> 00:14:15,117
I don't expect you to understand.

110
00:14:15,200 --> 00:14:18,075
Even pulling the trigger
on an empty gun was a-

111
00:14:18,158 --> 00:14:20,367
oh, a kind of cheating with myself.

112
00:14:20,408 --> 00:14:24,283
- It-It didn't prove anything. I did, you know?
- Oh, naturally.

113
00:14:24,367 --> 00:14:28,492
It had to be a loaded rifle
with my finger on the trigger...

114
00:14:28,575 --> 00:14:31,408
with only my individual will,
my civilized conscience...

115
00:14:31,450 --> 00:14:34,700
- between me and the extermination of your strutting little Caesar.
- Thorndike!

116
00:14:34,783 --> 00:14:38,908
I mean no insult, but how do you expect me
to describe a man who wants to play God...

117
00:14:38,950 --> 00:14:41,658
<i>and have everyone else in the world
run around and say, Heil Hitler"?</i>

118
00:14:41,700 --> 00:14:44,450
- Thorndike, I warn you.
- Oh, no, thank you.

119
00:15:02,992 --> 00:15:04,992
Oh.

120
00:15:07,325 --> 00:15:09,283
For the last time,
will you sign this document?

121
00:15:09,367 --> 00:15:12,450
You are in no position to refuse.

122
00:15:12,533 --> 00:15:14,908
That's for me to decide, isn't it?

123
00:15:14,992 --> 00:15:17,283
You're thinking it is easy
to throw away your life.

124
00:15:17,367 --> 00:15:19,783
Yes, it is.

125
00:15:19,867 --> 00:15:24,908
But, uh, how well do you stand pain?

126
00:15:24,992 --> 00:15:28,283
If you won't listen to me,
you'll have to talk it over with these men.

127
00:15:28,367 --> 00:15:31,200
I would save you from their persuasion.

128
00:15:33,242 --> 00:15:37,158
Very well.

129
00:16:15,450 --> 00:16:20,367
Tell him His Excellency, the German
ambassador, desires to speak with him.

130
00:16:21,825 --> 00:16:23,825
Of course he was there, sir-
all the time.

131
00:16:25,992 --> 00:16:29,408
- The German ambassador is on the telephone, my lord.
- What?

132
00:16:29,492 --> 00:16:32,700
Has a man no privacy even in his own home
in the middle of the night?

133
00:16:32,742 --> 00:16:35,492
I told him I would see
if you were still up, my lord.

134
00:16:35,575 --> 00:16:38,075
Oh, very well, very well.

135
00:16:38,158 --> 00:16:41,325
Hello. Hello.

136
00:16:41,408 --> 00:16:45,450
Yes, Risborough Speaking.
Uh, good evening, Your Excellency.

137
00:16:45,533 --> 00:16:48,533
A pleasure, I assure you.

138
00:16:48,575 --> 00:16:52,200
I heard some rumor that Captain Thorndike
is visiting our country.

139
00:16:52,242 --> 00:16:56,367
I'm sure I don't know, Your Excellency.
Have you called his club?

140
00:16:56,408 --> 00:17:02,033
I wish to telegraph my friends in Berlin
to see that he's taken care of properly.

141
00:17:05,033 --> 00:17:09,117
We cannot, of course, neglect any member
of Your LordShip's family.

142
00:17:09,200 --> 00:17:14,408
It's extremely gracious of Your Excellency,
but I'm sure you're mistaken.

143
00:17:14,492 --> 00:17:16,492
I haven't seen him for weeks.

144
00:17:16,575 --> 00:17:19,075
Sportsman, you know.

145
00:17:19,158 --> 00:17:23,867
Always running off to the end of the world
to catch a fish or some such nonsense.

146
00:17:23,908 --> 00:17:27,075
I'm positive he's not on the Continent.

147
00:17:27,117 --> 00:17:31,700
He may be on his ranch in Canada.
Spends a lot of time there.

148
00:17:31,783 --> 00:17:33,783
Not at all. Not at all.

149
00:17:33,867 --> 00:17:36,700
Why, a great pleasure, I assure you.

150
00:17:38,283 --> 00:17:43,242
The man is a fool,
but absolutely honest.

151
00:17:43,325 --> 00:17:45,783
The gestapo are a pack of-

152
00:17:47,492 --> 00:17:50,492
- Send this message to Berchtesgaden.
- Yes, sir.

153
00:17:51,908 --> 00:17:54,867
I should hesitate to
question the efficiency...

154
00:17:54,950 --> 00:17:57,658
of the gestapo agent...

155
00:17:57,700 --> 00:18:00,783
who claims to be holding Thorndike.

156
00:18:00,867 --> 00:18:04,992
But after my conversation
with Lord Risborough...

157
00:18:05,033 --> 00:18:09,783
I am convinced Thorndike
cannot possibly be your man.

158
00:18:09,825 --> 00:18:13,158
Clearly a case of mistaken identity.

159
00:18:13,242 --> 00:18:16,908
<i>Always glad to be of service. " Idiot.</i>

160
00:18:39,700 --> 00:18:42,992
<i>Doktor.</i>

161
00:19:17,325 --> 00:19:19,283
Thorndike.

162
00:19:20,408 --> 00:19:24,200
<i>Thorndike!</i>

163
00:19:24,242 --> 00:19:27,117
You're being exasperatingly
stubborn.

164
00:19:27,158 --> 00:19:30,283
You must realize that
this cannot Continue much longer.

165
00:19:30,367 --> 00:19:33,075
Are you ready to sign?

166
00:19:36,700 --> 00:19:40,200
Believe me, my dear fellow,
I don't want you to die.

167
00:19:43,783 --> 00:19:48,117
- Just sign your name and it'll be
important for us that you live.

168
00:19:48,200 --> 00:19:50,075
You will receive the best
of medical treatment.

169
00:19:50,158 --> 00:19:53,450
You will be free to go home,
free to live on that fine estate of yours...

170
00:19:53,533 --> 00:19:56,450
free to do anything you like,
except to leave England.

171
00:20:00,408 --> 00:20:03,242
Are you being so foolish as to
imagine yourself a martyr for England?

172
00:20:03,283 --> 00:20:05,950
Is that why you refuse?

173
00:20:06,033 --> 00:20:08,325
<i>- No.
- Why refuse then?</i>

174
00:20:08,408 --> 00:20:10,450
Why keep on torturing yourself?

175
00:20:10,533 --> 00:20:13,825
<i>Because I don't llke force.</i>

176
00:20:13,867 --> 00:20:17,950
<i>You force your own people
to keep In line, and...</i>

177
00:20:19,325 --> 00:20:21,283
<i>you think you can force
everyone else.</i>

178
00:20:21,367 --> 00:20:25,117
<i>Well, I'm one man saylng you can't.</i>

179
00:20:26,617 --> 00:20:28,617
<i>As you wish.</i>

180
00:20:28,700 --> 00:20:31,700
I'm not responsible for your suffering.

181
00:20:31,742 --> 00:20:34,617
You are, in fact, taking your own life.

182
00:20:40,408 --> 00:20:44,200
<i>That's going to be hard
to explain, Isn't It?</i>

183
00:20:44,283 --> 00:20:47,867
<i>- What is?
- My suicide.</i>

184
00:20:47,950 --> 00:20:50,783
<i>Lots of questions going to be asked.</i>

185
00:20:51,908 --> 00:20:56,117
<i>- High places.
- High places.</i>

186
00:20:58,950 --> 00:21:02,700
That's one place where
no questions will be asked.

187
00:21:02,742 --> 00:21:06,200
You've given me the key
I've been searching for.

188
00:21:07,492 --> 00:21:09,450
You won't change your mind
about this?

189
00:21:09,533 --> 00:21:12,617
<i>- Certainly not.
- Very well.</i>

190
00:21:12,700 --> 00:21:16,825
Identification is essential
in the High places.

191
00:21:16,867 --> 00:21:20,283
We'll give you back your passport
and your wallet, clean you up and-

192
00:21:20,367 --> 00:21:24,742
<i>Doktor.</i>

193
00:22:18,450 --> 00:22:20,408
<i>Doktor.</i>

194
00:22:37,700 --> 00:22:40,283
There are people in England that...

195
00:22:40,367 --> 00:22:44,117
know that men of my character
don't do this sort of thing.

196
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:47,492
Men of your character
have accidents.

197
00:22:47,575 --> 00:22:50,117
Tomorrow the Doktor and I
will go hunting.

198
00:22:50,158 --> 00:22:54,033
No one will question what we find
when we've found it.

199
00:22:54,117 --> 00:22:56,867
This ledge is treacherous.

200
00:27:49,200 --> 00:27:51,950
<i>The skipper ought to be back by now...</i>

201
00:27:52,033 --> 00:27:54,117
<i>If we're going to sail tonight.</i>

202
00:27:54,158 --> 00:27:57,033
<i>Right you are, sir.</i>

203
00:28:08,408 --> 00:28:12,033
If the blighters don't let us sail pretty soon,
we might as well all go ashore.

204
00:28:15,700 --> 00:28:18,158
- Good night.
- Good night.

205
00:28:47,408 --> 00:28:49,700
I say.

206
00:28:59,908 --> 00:29:01,867
<i>Ah, sein Paß.</i>

207
00:29:06,367 --> 00:29:09,658
My word. You seem to be
knocked about a bit.

208
00:29:10,992 --> 00:29:12,992
Yeah.

209
00:29:14,658 --> 00:29:16,867
Would you mind closing that door?

210
00:29:19,658 --> 00:29:23,408
- This is a British Ship, isn't it?
- Danish registry.

211
00:29:23,450 --> 00:29:26,700
- But you're British.
- Rather.

212
00:29:26,783 --> 00:29:30,825
Cabin boy. My father does business
with the captain out of Southampton.

213
00:29:30,908 --> 00:29:34,742
- I'm British too.
- Oh, I'd know you were British anywhere, sir.

214
00:29:36,408 --> 00:29:38,867
You seem to be in a bit of trouble, sir.

215
00:29:38,950 --> 00:29:43,533
Oh, more than a bit, I'm afraid.

216
00:29:46,700 --> 00:29:49,325
Have you committed a crime, sir?

217
00:29:49,408 --> 00:29:51,742
No.

218
00:29:51,825 --> 00:29:54,033
Was it, um...

219
00:29:55,450 --> 00:29:57,325
about a woman?

220
00:29:58,992 --> 00:30:02,700
I see you know life.

221
00:30:02,783 --> 00:30:04,992
I thought so.

222
00:30:05,033 --> 00:30:07,075
They're a dickens of a problem,
aren't they, sir?

223
00:30:11,700 --> 00:30:14,492
- Where are you bound?
- East India Docks, London.

224
00:30:14,533 --> 00:30:17,283
- And when are you sailing?
- Tonight, if we can get permission.

225
00:30:28,783 --> 00:30:30,950
This way, sir.
Quick!

226
00:30:34,533 --> 00:30:36,992
Come on, sir.
This way, sir.

227
00:30:37,075 --> 00:30:41,575
Hurry. Come on.
Come on! Come on!

228
00:30:42,867 --> 00:30:45,783
Hurry, sir. Come on.

229
00:30:51,992 --> 00:30:55,533
Oh, it's no use.
I haven't got the strength.

230
00:31:02,158 --> 00:31:04,158
They're coming!

231
00:31:06,200 --> 00:31:09,742
Quick. In here.

232
00:31:27,325 --> 00:31:29,325
Vaner!

233
00:31:33,075 --> 00:31:35,075
Vaner!

234
00:31:40,658 --> 00:31:42,617
<i>Donnerwetter.</i>

235
00:31:42,658 --> 00:31:44,658
Sorry, sir. I was belowdecks.

236
00:31:44,700 --> 00:31:47,825
Call your First mate. You c-

237
00:31:47,908 --> 00:31:51,825
Ah, there you are.
Already we waste two days.

238
00:31:51,908 --> 00:31:54,575
- We sail tonight as soon as these policemen search the Ship.
- Good.

239
00:31:54,658 --> 00:31:56,533
- Show them everything.
- Yeah.

240
00:31:56,617 --> 00:31:58,575
Then I get clearance, no?

241
00:31:58,658 --> 00:32:00,533
<i>- Danke.
- You will want to start belowdecks?</i>

242
00:32:00,617 --> 00:32:03,408
- Yes.
- This way, please.

243
00:32:03,450 --> 00:32:06,075
- Wait. I'll come with you.
- I'll take your coat, sir.

244
00:32:06,158 --> 00:32:09,200
- You might need it. It's cold on deck.
- You think so? All Right.

245
00:32:09,283 --> 00:32:11,492
Come. Come along.

246
00:32:30,700 --> 00:32:34,950
Only my own cabin you didn't search.
Is it not?

247
00:32:34,992 --> 00:32:37,367
Wait. Away, boy. Away.
I don't need you.

248
00:32:37,408 --> 00:32:39,700
Please. Go away.

249
00:32:43,533 --> 00:32:47,325
Maybe you think I would
hide stowaways, huh?

250
00:32:55,992 --> 00:33:00,492
Or maybe you think I hide
somebody under the mattress, no?

251
00:33:05,533 --> 00:33:07,742
<i>So, now we will sail, Is It not?</i>

252
00:33:07,825 --> 00:33:09,950
<i>- Certainly, Herr Kapitän.
- Danke.</i>

253
00:33:10,033 --> 00:33:12,700
<i>We only do our duty.
Herr Kapitän surely understands.</i>

254
00:33:12,742 --> 00:33:15,825
Certainly. Vaner.

255
00:33:15,908 --> 00:33:18,783
- Yes, sir.
- Tell the First mate we sail at once.

256
00:33:18,867 --> 00:33:21,325
Yes, sir.

257
00:33:21,367 --> 00:33:25,325
<i>Herr Kapitän, uh,
can you take a passenger?</i>

258
00:33:25,408 --> 00:33:28,700
Passenger? You mean he will pay?

259
00:33:28,742 --> 00:33:30,742
He has papers?

260
00:33:30,825 --> 00:33:34,075
He is English, but you
need have no doubt about him.

261
00:33:34,158 --> 00:33:36,325
His papers are in order,
and he has money.

262
00:33:36,408 --> 00:33:38,700
<i>Oh, here he is.</i>

263
00:33:43,117 --> 00:33:48,033
May I present, Captain Jensen,
Mr. Thorndike.

264
00:33:48,075 --> 00:33:50,492
- It's a pleasure, sir.
- How do you do?

265
00:33:50,575 --> 00:33:54,450
I'm not averse to paying whatever
you demand for my passage, Captain.

266
00:33:54,533 --> 00:33:57,700
You see, I have urgent business
in London.

267
00:33:57,700 --> 00:34:00,700
This is my passport, Captain.

268
00:34:56,658 --> 00:34:58,700
<i>Have I surprised you, Mr. Vaner?</i>

269
00:34:58,783 --> 00:35:00,992
I thought I saw you go ashore, sir.

270
00:35:01,033 --> 00:35:05,950
Ah, yes. But I forgot
to say good-bye to the captain.

271
00:35:06,033 --> 00:35:08,033
But he's not here?

272
00:35:08,117 --> 00:35:10,283
Captain Jensen's on deck, sir.

273
00:35:10,367 --> 00:35:13,658
He's going ashore with the cargo manifest.
You may miss him if you wait here.

274
00:35:13,700 --> 00:35:15,700
Ah, yes.

275
00:35:21,533 --> 00:35:25,533
It's easy to miss a man
aboard Ship now, isn't it, Mr. Vaner?

276
00:35:32,117 --> 00:35:37,367
Oh, I thought you leave us when you told me
good-bye. You forget something, yes?

277
00:35:37,408 --> 00:35:40,700
I'm a very forgetful man, Captain.
Always forgetting the obvious.

278
00:35:40,742 --> 00:35:43,825
- It's my failing.
- Come. I take you ashore with me.

279
00:35:43,908 --> 00:35:46,367
Thank you, sir.
Thank you.

280
00:36:16,075 --> 00:36:18,658
Hello.

281
00:36:37,575 --> 00:36:39,867
Isn't this going to get you
into trouble?

282
00:36:39,908 --> 00:36:41,825
Oh, probably, sir, but I don't mind.

283
00:36:41,908 --> 00:36:44,950
It won't be the First time the First mate
and I have had our differences.

284
00:36:50,700 --> 00:36:53,908
I don't think you ought
to leave the Ship yet, sir.

285
00:36:53,992 --> 00:36:57,033
Stop worrying, my boy.
This is England. I'm home again.

286
00:36:57,117 --> 00:36:59,283
But I didn't like the looks
of that walking corpse.

287
00:36:59,367 --> 00:37:01,783
Kept sniffing around the whole voyage.

288
00:37:01,825 --> 00:37:05,492
From the way you described him, I've never
laid eyes on the man or he on me.

289
00:37:05,533 --> 00:37:07,742
Smell that London air.

290
00:37:07,783 --> 00:37:11,533
I'm not worrying anymore,
thank heaven. Thanks to you.

291
00:37:13,367 --> 00:37:18,700
You know, Vaner, there are some things
that words can't express.

292
00:37:18,783 --> 00:37:21,658
And just between us men...

293
00:37:21,700 --> 00:37:25,367
I don't know how to thank you,
so I'm not going to try.

294
00:37:25,450 --> 00:37:28,742
- You've taken me on trust, my boy.
- Of course, sir.

295
00:37:31,158 --> 00:37:33,283
Ah, thank you.

296
00:37:34,325 --> 00:37:37,533
- Just one thing, sir.
- Huh?

297
00:37:38,783 --> 00:37:41,158
It wasn't a woman, was it, sir?

298
00:37:41,242 --> 00:37:43,825
- No.
- I thought so.

299
00:37:47,283 --> 00:37:51,700
- Good luck, sir, and be careful.
- Thank you.

300
00:37:51,783 --> 00:37:53,992
Would you mind seeing
if the coast is clear?

301
00:37:57,533 --> 00:38:00,242
- All Right.
- Good-bye, old boy.

302
00:38:47,033 --> 00:38:50,158
<i>?It's the same the whole world over?</i>

303
00:38:50,242 --> 00:38:53,742
<i>?It's the poor what gets the blame?</i>

304
00:38:53,825 --> 00:38:56,950
? While the rich has all the pleasures?

305
00:38:57,033 --> 00:39:01,117
? Now ain't that a blinkin' shame?

306
00:39:01,200 --> 00:39:04,700
? She was a just a parson's daughter?

307
00:39:08,075 --> 00:39:10,158
I say, what Ship, matey?

308
00:39:10,242 --> 00:39:12,825
<i>Uh, the, uh- the Lifeline.</i>

309
00:39:12,867 --> 00:39:15,825
- Well, welcome home.
- Thanks, old chap.

310
00:39:47,700 --> 00:39:50,658
- Taxi, sir?
- Yes.

311
00:39:56,158 --> 00:39:58,700
<i>Back up! Follow him!</i>

312
00:41:43,742 --> 00:41:45,492
Don't open the door.

313
00:41:45,533 --> 00:41:47,825
- Let me go. What you doin' here?
- Shh!

314
00:41:47,908 --> 00:41:49,325
<i>- Let me go!
- Quiet.</i>

315
00:41:49,408 --> 00:41:51,867
Let me go or I'll call the co-

316
00:42:32,908 --> 00:42:36,158
Oh, thank you, my dear.
You saved my life.

317
00:42:36,242 --> 00:42:39,450
Saved your life?

318
00:42:39,492 --> 00:42:41,658
Here, who are you anyway?

319
00:42:41,700 --> 00:42:44,992
Well, I was laboring under the delusion
that I was a carefree man...

320
00:42:45,075 --> 00:42:49,825
returning home for the fatted calf,
and now I realize I am the fatted calf.

321
00:42:49,867 --> 00:42:52,200
Wish you'd say things
I can understand.

322
00:42:52,242 --> 00:42:55,242
Uh, have you got a cigarette?

323
00:42:55,283 --> 00:42:57,200
Thank you very much.

324
00:42:57,283 --> 00:42:59,242
Who are them blokes
what are after you?

325
00:42:59,283 --> 00:43:02,325
You won't believe me when I tell you
I've never before laid eyes on them.

326
00:43:02,408 --> 00:43:04,700
How do you know
they're after you then?

327
00:43:04,700 --> 00:43:08,492
When one's been hunted, my dear child,
one develops instincts. It's amazing.

328
00:43:08,575 --> 00:43:10,450
Did you commit a murder?

329
00:43:10,533 --> 00:43:14,575
Mm-mmm. However, I suspect
that something of that nature...

330
00:43:14,658 --> 00:43:17,700
was about to be committed
when you came to the rescue of the victim.

331
00:43:17,742 --> 00:43:21,033
So, uh, once again,
my dear, thank you.

332
00:43:21,117 --> 00:43:24,700
Your memory will be imperishable
as long as I live.

333
00:43:24,742 --> 00:43:28,200
And, uh, just how long that will be
depends again on you.

334
00:43:28,242 --> 00:43:31,283
Now see here. I ain't gettin'
mixed up in nothin'. I can tell you that.

335
00:43:31,367 --> 00:43:35,033
Heaven forbid. The last thing in the world
I want to do is involve an innocent.

336
00:43:35,117 --> 00:43:38,617
But I need the loan of a few shillings.
Uh, a pound, if you have it.

337
00:43:38,700 --> 00:43:40,700
Ah. You talks like a gentleman...

338
00:43:40,742 --> 00:43:43,242
but gents don't go around
askin' girls for money.

339
00:43:43,325 --> 00:43:46,408
You've probably never before
entertained a desperate gentleman.

340
00:43:46,492 --> 00:43:49,325
I've simply got to get to
my brother's house in Grosvenor Gardens.

341
00:43:49,367 --> 00:43:51,783
Grosvenor Gardens?
Go on.

342
00:43:53,742 --> 00:43:56,408
It should be obvious that
I can't get that far on foot...

343
00:43:56,492 --> 00:43:58,492
especially with
these other gentlemen in the street.

344
00:43:58,575 --> 00:44:01,533
I need a cab. I may have to
change to sundry other cabs.

345
00:44:01,617 --> 00:44:05,367
And, uh, unfortunately,
when I left my private yacht...

346
00:44:05,450 --> 00:44:07,408
I neglected to put
a stiver in my pocket.

347
00:44:07,450 --> 00:44:09,950
I am for the moment
absolutely penniless.

348
00:44:10,033 --> 00:44:11,992
Come off it.

349
00:44:13,033 --> 00:44:15,783
I, uh, see you don't trust me.

350
00:44:17,908 --> 00:44:19,742
Well...

351
00:44:21,283 --> 00:44:24,700
allow me to thank you at any rate
for the great service you've done me.

352
00:44:24,783 --> 00:44:26,783
I shall have to risk it on foot.

353
00:44:38,200 --> 00:44:40,742
- Bye.
- Half a mo.

354
00:44:42,367 --> 00:44:46,075
Will-Will 10 bob do?

355
00:44:47,908 --> 00:44:50,658
It's all I got.

356
00:44:54,825 --> 00:44:57,408
To lend all you've got
is a pretty big loan.

357
00:44:58,825 --> 00:45:01,283
Unless something unavoidable
happens to me...

358
00:45:01,367 --> 00:45:04,492
you shall get this back
with tenfold interest.

359
00:45:41,992 --> 00:45:43,908
- I'm going with you.
- Oh, no.

360
00:45:43,992 --> 00:45:45,950
I ain't afraid!
You can't stop me.

361
00:45:45,992 --> 00:45:49,033
- You're coming to make sure you get your money, is that it?
- Right.

362
00:45:49,117 --> 00:45:52,908
You wait here where you're safe.
I'll get a cabbie who's a pal of mine.

363
00:46:09,533 --> 00:46:11,908
Don't stand there coughing, Reeves.
What is it?

364
00:46:11,950 --> 00:46:15,367
- It's Mr. Alan, my lord.
- Mr. Alan?

365
00:46:15,450 --> 00:46:17,783
Yes, with a young lady, my lord.

366
00:46:17,867 --> 00:46:21,200
Gerald, old boy. Bless my soul,
it's good to see you.

367
00:46:21,283 --> 00:46:23,700
Alice, my dear.

368
00:46:23,742 --> 00:46:26,658
Alan! Your face. This scar.

369
00:46:26,700 --> 00:46:31,075
Oh, those revolting clothes.
What has happened to you?

370
00:46:31,158 --> 00:46:33,742
- Allow me to shake your hand too, Reeves.
- Oh.

371
00:46:33,825 --> 00:46:36,075
<i>Alan. Come In my study.</i>

372
00:46:36,158 --> 00:46:39,408
I must see you alone...
immediately.

373
00:46:39,533 --> 00:46:43,575
Don't be so impatient, Gerald.
I feel like shaking hands with everybody.

374
00:46:43,617 --> 00:46:45,533
How are you, Reeves?

375
00:46:45,617 --> 00:46:48,408
And you, sir.
How are you?

376
00:46:51,575 --> 00:46:54,283
Oh, Alice.

377
00:46:54,325 --> 00:46:57,325
Allow me to present
a very dear friend of mine.

378
00:46:57,408 --> 00:46:59,783
This is Miss, uh-

379
00:46:59,867 --> 00:47:03,492
- That's odd. What is your name?
- Jerry. Jerry Stokes.

380
00:47:03,575 --> 00:47:05,492
Lord and Lady Risborough,
Miss Jerry Stokes.

381
00:47:05,575 --> 00:47:07,575
- Uh, how do you do?
- Hello.

382
00:47:07,617 --> 00:47:10,575
Pleased to meet you, ma'am.

383
00:47:12,283 --> 00:47:15,783
- How do you do?
- I must talk to you. It's very important.

384
00:47:15,867 --> 00:47:18,325
Yes, of course. First,
have you got a fiver in your pocket?

385
00:47:18,408 --> 00:47:20,700
But, my dear boy,
this is most urgent.

386
00:47:20,700 --> 00:47:23,242
But no more so than this.
Come on. A fiver, please.

387
00:47:23,283 --> 00:47:25,325
- Oh, very well, then.
- Thanks very much.

388
00:47:25,408 --> 00:47:27,408
- Now-
- Just a half a minute.

389
00:47:27,450 --> 00:47:29,367
There you are, my dear.

390
00:47:29,450 --> 00:47:33,367
- That's for you and a thousand thanks.
- You don't owe me all that.

391
00:47:33,450 --> 00:47:37,950
<i>Of course I do, and a great deal more
than I can repay with money. Here.</i>

392
00:47:40,533 --> 00:47:42,533
I- I ain't gonna take it.

393
00:47:42,617 --> 00:47:45,533
Don't you get stubborn with me,
young lady. You want to be choked again?

394
00:47:45,617 --> 00:47:47,658
<i>- Alan!
- Here.</i>

395
00:47:47,700 --> 00:47:50,950
<i>- Alan.
- I tell you there's not a moment to waste.</i>

396
00:47:51,033 --> 00:47:52,992
Certainly, sir. I shan't be a moment.

397
00:47:53,033 --> 00:47:55,700
Alice, I'm sure you and Miss Stokes
will find much to talk about.

398
00:47:55,742 --> 00:47:58,533
- Do you mind if I keep this? I might need it later on.
- Sure.

399
00:47:58,617 --> 00:48:01,825
Five quid! Lummy.

400
00:48:01,867 --> 00:48:05,533
Wish I could meet a bloke like 'im
every day. And me thinkin' he was balmy!

401
00:48:05,617 --> 00:48:08,075
Imagine!

402
00:48:09,117 --> 00:48:12,492
Uh, won't you sit here?

403
00:48:14,992 --> 00:48:18,283
Ooh. This is comfy, ain't it?

404
00:48:18,325 --> 00:48:22,992
<i>Great heavens, Alan. How could
you have got yourself In this awful mess?</i>

405
00:48:23,075 --> 00:48:25,033
How did you know about it?

406
00:48:25,117 --> 00:48:29,367
Their embassy's been making polite
inquiries about you for nearly four weeks.

407
00:48:29,450 --> 00:48:32,700
Lately, they've become
more persistent, more pointed.

408
00:48:32,700 --> 00:48:35,742
Then not 10 minutes ago,
the foreign office telephoned...

409
00:48:35,825 --> 00:48:39,867
that our agents in Berlin
say that you're secretly accused of-

410
00:48:39,908 --> 00:48:43,283
- of an attempt upon the life of their führer.
- Ah!

411
00:48:43,367 --> 00:48:46,658
I told them, of course,
that the suggestion was fantastic...

412
00:48:46,700 --> 00:48:49,325
that there was absolutely no basis
in fact for such an accusation...

413
00:48:49,367 --> 00:48:52,742
that you couldn't possibly
be involved in any such affair.

414
00:48:53,908 --> 00:48:55,867
That is the truth, isn't it?

415
00:48:56,867 --> 00:48:58,783
Yes, Gerald.

416
00:48:58,825 --> 00:49:02,658
Thank heaven. Then you'll go straight with me
to the embassy and clear the matter up at once.

417
00:49:02,700 --> 00:49:05,367
- I'm afraid I can't.
- In heaven's name, why not?

418
00:49:05,450 --> 00:49:09,617
Uh, sit down, Gerald.

419
00:49:14,908 --> 00:49:17,742
Young woman, what is
your connection with Alan?

420
00:49:20,742 --> 00:49:22,742
Alan.

421
00:49:22,825 --> 00:49:24,742
Is that his name?

422
00:49:24,825 --> 00:49:27,408
You-You don't know him?

423
00:49:27,492 --> 00:49:29,700
Never laid me eyes on him
before tonight.

424
00:49:29,700 --> 00:49:33,408
He's a bit of all Right though
if you ask me. A real swell.

425
00:49:33,492 --> 00:49:35,950
I say, what's this jam
he's got mixed up in?

426
00:49:36,033 --> 00:49:39,408
- Are the rozzers after him?
- The-The-The what?

427
00:49:39,492 --> 00:49:42,450
Rozzers!

428
00:49:42,533 --> 00:49:45,783
Dicks! Coppers. Policemen.

429
00:49:45,825 --> 00:49:48,700
Oh, yes, policemen.

430
00:49:48,700 --> 00:49:51,283
Hmm?

431
00:49:51,367 --> 00:49:53,367
Hmm.

432
00:49:54,617 --> 00:49:57,033
- Good, ain't it?
- Mmm.

433
00:49:58,867 --> 00:50:01,992
But, Gerald, old boy, I did not sign
their faked-up confession.

434
00:50:02,033 --> 00:50:04,700
But they won't need it
if they can get you back into Germany.

435
00:50:04,742 --> 00:50:07,325
- They've got to catch me First.
- Oh, but they-

436
00:50:07,408 --> 00:50:10,200
- they know you're in London.
- In that case, I shall get out of England.

437
00:50:10,283 --> 00:50:13,575
But that's impossible too.
You have no passport.

438
00:50:13,658 --> 00:50:17,492
Any effort to obtain a new one
would only involve the government.

439
00:50:17,575 --> 00:50:21,367
Besides, every Ship and plane
leaving the country will be watched.

440
00:50:21,408 --> 00:50:23,408
What about Scotland Yard?

441
00:50:23,450 --> 00:50:25,575
Within 24 hours, there'd
be a démarche on my desk...

442
00:50:25,658 --> 00:50:28,033
asking for your arrest
and return to Berlin.

443
00:50:28,075 --> 00:50:31,117
To refuse their ambassador,
that would be an unfriendly act.

444
00:50:31,200 --> 00:50:34,075
We would have no choice
but to comply.

445
00:50:36,575 --> 00:50:39,325
You know what would happen then?

446
00:50:39,408 --> 00:50:42,325
You mean I might even have the honor
of having my head lobbed off...

447
00:50:42,408 --> 00:50:44,575
by the First headsman of the Reich?

448
00:50:44,658 --> 00:50:48,617
I mean there would First
be a faked-up trial.

449
00:50:48,700 --> 00:50:50,617
Not you...

450
00:50:50,700 --> 00:50:54,158
but England would be convicted
before the world.

451
00:50:54,242 --> 00:50:57,075
And that would pave the way
for what they want-

452
00:50:57,158 --> 00:50:59,075
war.

453
00:50:59,158 --> 00:51:01,992
Don't forget their Reichstag Fire Trial.

454
00:51:02,075 --> 00:51:06,908
You know their genius
for producing witnesses and documents...

455
00:51:06,950 --> 00:51:09,825
to prove their enemies guilty
of what they intend to do.

456
00:51:09,867 --> 00:51:14,742
In that case, I shall imitate their gestapo
and become invisible myself.

457
00:51:14,825 --> 00:51:18,617
I shall vanish utterly, completely,
as if I were dead for as long as you wish.

458
00:51:18,658 --> 00:51:20,575
I'll see no one- not even you.

459
00:51:20,658 --> 00:51:23,283
If I could only help you.

460
00:51:23,325 --> 00:51:25,242
But you can, old boy,
by not worrying.

461
00:51:25,325 --> 00:51:27,867
This whole thing will blow over
before long. It's bound to.

462
00:51:27,908 --> 00:51:29,950
In the meantime,
I give you my word of honor:

463
00:51:30,033 --> 00:51:33,617
<i>There'll be no confession, no trial.</i>

464
00:51:35,242 --> 00:51:37,700
Gerald, I've got one of
my dreadful headaches coming on.

465
00:51:37,742 --> 00:51:40,992
- I'm afraid you'll have to excuse me.
- Why, yes, of course, my dear.

466
00:51:41,033 --> 00:51:43,158
I've left that young person
in the living room. Don't-

467
00:51:43,242 --> 00:51:46,117
Alice, I never thought you'd be
the First to throw up the sponge.

468
00:51:46,158 --> 00:51:48,700
- Come on. You've got to see Jerry at the door.
- No, I shan't.

469
00:51:48,700 --> 00:51:52,033
- But after all, she's your guest, you know?
- I can't. I really can't.

470
00:51:52,117 --> 00:51:54,158
Remember, she thinks you're a lady.

471
00:51:54,242 --> 00:51:58,117
Surely you don't want to disillusion
anyone so young and trusting.

472
00:51:58,200 --> 00:52:00,117
Ah.

473
00:52:04,408 --> 00:52:07,617
Here. You looks like the gentleman
who asked me to have dinner with him...

474
00:52:07,658 --> 00:52:10,158
at Lyons Corner House last bank holiday.

475
00:52:10,242 --> 00:52:12,908
I? Well, I'm not the gentleman, miss.

476
00:52:12,992 --> 00:52:15,242
In fact, I'm not a gentleman at all.

477
00:52:15,283 --> 00:52:19,450
You're the spittin' image of him then,
but you do act more scaredy like.

478
00:52:19,492 --> 00:52:22,075
<i>Now, miss-</i>

479
00:52:24,658 --> 00:52:28,992
Jerry, Lord and Lady Risborough
wish to say good night.

480
00:52:29,033 --> 00:52:33,492
This the First time anything like this
ever happened to me. I'll never forget it.

481
00:52:33,575 --> 00:52:37,367
Good night, Mr. Reeves.
And it was Lyons Corner House.

482
00:52:37,450 --> 00:52:40,908
<i>Good night.</i>

483
00:52:40,992 --> 00:52:42,908
Good night.

484
00:52:42,992 --> 00:52:44,700
- Uh, good night.
- Good night.

485
00:52:44,783 --> 00:52:47,283
- Good night, Alice. Hope to see you very soon.
- Good night, Alan.

486
00:52:47,367 --> 00:52:49,950
Come along, Jerry. Gerald,
I don't know just how I'll work it...

487
00:52:50,033 --> 00:52:53,367
but somehow I'll get word to you
and let you know what's up.

488
00:52:53,450 --> 00:52:55,408
Well, I'll wait till I hear from you.

489
00:52:55,450 --> 00:52:58,158
Beg pardon, my lord. Major Smith
is calling on the telephone again.

490
00:52:58,200 --> 00:53:00,742
- I'm not at home. Well, good night.
- Good night, old chum.

491
00:53:00,825 --> 00:53:03,783
Wait. It's you he wants.

492
00:53:03,867 --> 00:53:05,825
- Who?
- Major Quive-Smith.

493
00:53:05,908 --> 00:53:09,325
- Quive-Smith?
- Yes. He called my office yesterday.

494
00:53:09,367 --> 00:53:13,658
He said he was a neighbor of yours-
a retired military man from the west of England.

495
00:53:13,700 --> 00:53:16,533
- What's he look like?
- Tall, good figure.

496
00:53:16,575 --> 00:53:19,783
Rather formal. Talks about Kenya.
You know the type.

497
00:53:19,867 --> 00:53:21,992
Talks about Kenya?
Does he wear a monocle?

498
00:53:22,075 --> 00:53:24,033
That's the fellow, yes.

499
00:53:24,075 --> 00:53:26,158
- Did he ask if I were here?
- Yes, sir, he did.

500
00:53:26,242 --> 00:53:30,533
<i>- You told him? - Yes, sir. You see,
knowing he was an old friend, I thought-</i>

501
00:53:30,617 --> 00:53:33,033
- Gerald, take that call, will you?
- Well, what should I tell him?

502
00:53:33,117 --> 00:53:36,742
Tell him, uh-
Tell him I've just left for the club.

503
00:53:36,825 --> 00:53:39,450
Good-bye, old chap.

504
00:53:39,533 --> 00:53:42,117
Don't you worry.

505
00:53:42,158 --> 00:53:44,492
Come on.

506
00:53:50,033 --> 00:53:53,033
- Gerald, what is all this cursed mystery?
- Alice.

507
00:53:53,117 --> 00:53:57,075
Ambassadors telephoning? Scotland Yard
phoning? Major Qui Vive on the qui vive.

508
00:53:57,158 --> 00:54:00,033
Alan looking like a police character
with his face clawed like a tiger or something.

509
00:54:00,117 --> 00:54:02,033
He's mad. Perfectly mad! Insane.

510
00:54:02,117 --> 00:54:04,033
- If you want my advice, you'll call the rozzers.
- Rozzer-

511
00:54:04,117 --> 00:54:06,117
- Dicks!
- Di-

512
00:54:17,617 --> 00:54:19,825
All clear, matey!

513
00:54:26,575 --> 00:54:29,158
<i>- Oh, crumbs!
- Huh?</i>

514
00:54:29,242 --> 00:54:31,700
My pin.
Me good luck pin.

515
00:54:31,783 --> 00:54:34,158
It must have fell off
when I dropped me tam.

516
00:54:34,242 --> 00:54:37,575
It was an heart.
Little stones on it all sparkly.

517
00:54:37,617 --> 00:54:39,617
- A gentleman give it me.
- Oh!

518
00:54:39,700 --> 00:54:42,408
- Oh, drat!
- Hey, hey.

519
00:54:42,450 --> 00:54:45,533
In that case, a gentleman
will give you another one.

520
00:54:45,617 --> 00:54:48,283
That's the least I can do for you, isn't it?

521
00:54:48,325 --> 00:54:51,200
You're not half as grown up
as you pretend to be, are you, Jerry?

522
00:54:51,242 --> 00:54:53,700
Now you're making fun of me again.

523
00:56:05,325 --> 00:56:08,283
- Only a flatfoot. I know 'im.
- Oh.

524
00:56:10,408 --> 00:56:13,325
From now on I'll distrust
everybody but you, Jerry.

525
00:56:13,408 --> 00:56:16,950
Get yourself some sleep. I'm going to
curl up on the couch. Good night.

526
00:56:18,242 --> 00:56:20,200
Good night.

527
00:56:53,075 --> 00:56:56,117
Jerry.

528
00:56:56,200 --> 00:57:00,075
What the devil are you
sniffling about? Huh?

529
00:57:00,117 --> 00:57:02,658
<i>What Is It?</i>

530
00:57:02,700 --> 00:57:06,158
My dear child, come on now.

531
00:57:06,200 --> 00:57:08,575
Come on.
No more of this.

532
00:57:08,617 --> 00:57:11,242
Let's stop the crying, what?
That's a girl.

533
00:57:11,325 --> 00:57:13,658
Now, a great big smile.
Come on.

534
00:57:13,700 --> 00:57:16,533
Great big smile.
That's better.

535
00:57:16,617 --> 00:57:18,617
Much better.

536
00:57:21,033 --> 00:57:22,992
Good night.

537
00:57:27,783 --> 00:57:30,325
Good night.

538
00:57:59,242 --> 00:58:01,950
- Oh, good morning, ducky.
- Morning.

539
00:58:03,450 --> 00:58:06,033
I was just on the point
of breaking that door down.

540
00:58:06,117 --> 00:58:08,575
Well, I couldn't leave it
unlocked, could I?

541
00:58:08,617 --> 00:58:10,825
That's Right.
I never thought of that.

542
00:58:10,908 --> 00:58:15,242
And by the way, my girl, who put
that coverlet over me while I slept?

543
00:58:15,325 --> 00:58:18,533
- Don't know. Just got there, I suppose.
- Mmm. I smell food.

544
00:58:18,617 --> 00:58:22,158
- Fish and chips.
- What a miraculous aroma.

545
00:58:22,200 --> 00:58:24,617
If that's as good as it smells-

546
00:58:28,700 --> 00:58:31,617
Come. Sit down.

547
00:58:40,242 --> 00:58:42,200
Ahh.

548
00:58:47,117 --> 00:58:49,408
Go on. Company First.

549
00:58:49,492 --> 00:58:51,450
Um, uh-

550
00:58:54,117 --> 00:58:56,783
- Well, what-
- How does one, uh-

551
00:58:56,867 --> 00:58:59,575
With your fingers, silly, like this.

552
00:58:59,658 --> 00:59:02,200
Mmm. Of course.

553
00:59:02,283 --> 00:59:04,867
I forgot. The fingers
came before forks.

554
00:59:04,908 --> 00:59:07,367
Ain't you never had
fish and chips afore?

555
00:59:07,450 --> 00:59:10,450
- This can't be fish and chips.
- Course it is.

556
00:59:10,533 --> 00:59:13,117
Just think what I've
been missing all my life, huh?

557
00:59:13,200 --> 00:59:15,950
Come on. Dig in, my girl,
before I get your share.

558
00:59:22,992 --> 00:59:26,325
Mmm. That's good.

559
00:59:36,617 --> 00:59:39,325
What's the matter, Jerry?

560
00:59:39,408 --> 00:59:42,283
<i>- You know somethin'?
- What?</i>

561
00:59:42,367 --> 00:59:45,533
- I don't like gentlemen.
- Like me, you mean?

562
00:59:45,575 --> 00:59:47,908
Oh, no.

563
00:59:47,950 --> 00:59:50,700
You act like a gent, but you ain't.

564
00:59:50,742 --> 00:59:54,617
I mean, you really acts like a gent.

565
00:59:56,075 --> 00:59:58,783
Well, that's a very
complicated statement, Jerry.

566
01:00:00,200 --> 01:00:02,492
Shall I tell you something?

567
01:00:02,533 --> 01:00:07,575
You have great character. You're an
extraordinary girl and a very pretty one too.

568
01:00:07,658 --> 01:00:10,617
Come on. Eat up there.

569
01:00:15,242 --> 01:00:17,200
Where you goin'?

570
01:00:20,700 --> 01:00:22,908
Far away.

571
01:00:22,992 --> 01:00:26,783
Soon I'll have money, and I'll be able to
give the gentleman with the monocle the slip...

572
01:00:26,825 --> 01:00:29,367
till I get on board a liner.

573
01:00:29,408 --> 01:00:32,325
- Gentleman with a monocle?
- Uh, the headman, Jerry.

574
01:00:32,408 --> 01:00:34,783
You saw some of his minions
last night.

575
01:00:34,825 --> 01:00:39,075
- Oh. Hmm.
- They're just small fry.

576
01:00:39,158 --> 01:00:41,867
I think that you'd better
come along with me.

577
01:00:45,033 --> 01:00:47,658
- On a Ship?
- Oh, good heavens, no.

578
01:00:47,700 --> 01:00:49,700
To my solicitors, I mean.

579
01:00:49,783 --> 01:00:54,033
I can't come back here, and I want you
to have some money for all you've done.

580
01:01:03,450 --> 01:01:07,533
I can't leave England, my dear, without knowing
that you have something for your old age-

581
01:01:07,617 --> 01:01:09,617
a woman of your advanced years.

582
01:01:09,700 --> 01:01:14,408
My greatest anxiety last night was
in getting you mixed up in my affairs.

583
01:01:14,492 --> 01:01:16,492
And-

584
01:01:16,575 --> 01:01:20,700
Say, on second thought,
maybe you'd better not come along.

585
01:01:20,742 --> 01:01:23,200
I could have Saul
deliver the funds to you here.

586
01:01:23,283 --> 01:01:26,033
- Oh, no.
- Yeah, I think it'd be safer.

587
01:01:26,117 --> 01:01:29,700
I don't believe they'd hang around
Saul's office. It's too near the law courts.

588
01:01:29,783 --> 01:01:32,742
- But they might.
- What about you?

589
01:01:32,825 --> 01:01:34,825
Huh? Oh, I can shake 'em all Right.

590
01:01:34,908 --> 01:01:38,700
It's amazing how reassuring the sunlight is,
but I was pretty jumpy last night.

591
01:01:38,783 --> 01:01:42,533
- I'm going along.
- But there's no point in it, no use at all.

592
01:01:46,783 --> 01:01:49,075
How do I know
I'm gonna get what-

593
01:01:50,783 --> 01:01:53,158
what you promised me?

594
01:01:56,450 --> 01:01:59,908
So you don't trust me, huh?

595
01:02:01,783 --> 01:02:03,783
I always pay my debts.

596
01:02:03,867 --> 01:02:07,325
<i>I propose to get you £500.
You may have more, If you want It.</i>

597
01:02:12,117 --> 01:02:14,200
I don't mean money.

598
01:02:17,242 --> 01:02:19,575
Well, what in heaven's name
do you mean?

599
01:02:19,658 --> 01:02:23,408
You promised me...

600
01:02:23,492 --> 01:02:27,075
a pin for me hat.

601
01:02:30,325 --> 01:02:34,325
My dear Jerry, forgive me.

602
01:02:34,367 --> 01:02:36,700
I might have known.

603
01:02:36,742 --> 01:02:40,367
Every good soldier needs
a crest for his cap.

604
01:02:40,450 --> 01:02:43,450
And you shall have your pin
set with diamonds, if you wish.

605
01:02:43,492 --> 01:02:45,783
Huh?

606
01:02:45,867 --> 01:02:47,867
Mmm.

607
01:03:04,908 --> 01:03:08,117
<i>- Good morning.
- Good morning, mein Herr. Good morning, fräulein.</i>

608
01:03:09,533 --> 01:03:12,033
What shall it be?

609
01:03:12,117 --> 01:03:16,408
Uh- Uh, you've got a, um-

610
01:03:16,450 --> 01:03:18,908
a pin, sort of a brooch,
in the Window.

611
01:03:18,992 --> 01:03:22,200
<i>Ja. Ja. I show it to you.</i>

612
01:03:22,283 --> 01:03:24,283
It's a large heart.

613
01:03:24,367 --> 01:03:27,825
You know what? I don't want an heart.
It's too much like-

614
01:03:27,908 --> 01:03:30,533
Like the one you lost.
That's what you want, isn't it?

615
01:03:30,617 --> 01:03:34,867
So beautiful that piece of jewelry
and so fine a sentiment- the heart.

616
01:03:34,950 --> 01:03:38,533
<i>You see, fräulein? It's gold plate,
and the fine stones just like diamonds.</i>

617
01:03:38,617 --> 01:03:40,783
You know, I think
it's rather appropriate.

618
01:03:40,867 --> 01:03:43,825
<i>- How much is this one?
- Ten shillings, fräulein.</i>

619
01:03:43,908 --> 01:03:47,533
Very cheap. It costs you
two guineas on Regent Street.

620
01:03:47,617 --> 01:03:51,033
You should have that and
put it in the gentleman's heart, no?

621
01:03:51,117 --> 01:03:53,117
Is it real silver?

622
01:03:53,200 --> 01:03:55,575
Better. It's chromium.

623
01:03:57,533 --> 01:04:00,575
<i>- Can I have it?
- Well, Certainly, if you want to be heartless.</i>

624
01:04:00,617 --> 01:04:03,158
<i>Good, good.
You make no mistake, fräulein.</i>

625
01:04:03,242 --> 01:04:07,575
A lifetime, I tell you.
You will have it still when you die.

626
01:04:07,658 --> 01:04:10,950
- Go on. Take it.
- No. You've got to give it me.

627
01:04:10,992 --> 01:04:13,033
I- Oh.

628
01:04:14,992 --> 01:04:17,783
I present you with
this dangerous weapon, mademoiselle...

629
01:04:17,867 --> 01:04:20,658
with my undying gratitude
and admiration.

630
01:04:20,700 --> 01:04:23,533
May you never lodge it
in the wrong heart.

631
01:04:29,242 --> 01:04:31,908
- There you are, sir.
- One pound, 20 shillings. I give you change.

632
01:04:31,950 --> 01:04:35,992
No, keep it, keep it. There mustn't be
anything mercenary about this soldier's crest.

633
01:04:36,075 --> 01:04:39,908
<i>- It's got to bring luck.
- Danke. Danke. Danke, mein Herr.</i>

634
01:04:42,033 --> 01:04:46,200
I think that looks very nice.
Don't you? Huh? Shall we go?

635
01:04:46,283 --> 01:04:48,867
<i>- Come on.
- Auf Wiedersehen. Auf Wiedersehen.</i>

636
01:04:48,908 --> 01:04:50,158
<i>- Good-bye.
- Auf Wiedersehen.</i>

637
01:05:44,825 --> 01:05:47,492
<i>Ja?</i>

638
01:05:50,908 --> 01:05:54,117
<i>Heil Hitler.</i>

639
01:05:54,200 --> 01:05:56,200
Six.

640
01:05:57,242 --> 01:05:59,283
Farnsworthy's office.

641
01:06:07,658 --> 01:06:11,242
Well, uh, it isn't
exactly, uh, Savile Row.

642
01:06:11,325 --> 01:06:15,200
It was the best I could do. After all,
you phoned less than an hour ago.

643
01:06:15,283 --> 01:06:17,242
Well.

644
01:06:20,617 --> 01:06:24,158
Well, uh, aren't you going to
ask any questions?

645
01:06:24,242 --> 01:06:26,908
Only one.

646
01:06:26,992 --> 01:06:29,617
Have you been abroad
in the employ of our government?

647
01:06:29,700 --> 01:06:33,492
- No, on my own business.
- I beg you to let me talk to the police.

648
01:06:33,575 --> 01:06:35,575
You don't realize
the power of your name.

649
01:06:35,658 --> 01:06:38,783
That is precisely what makes
my disappearance necessary and urgent.

650
01:06:38,825 --> 01:06:40,867
But, my dear chap, don't you realize-

651
01:06:40,908 --> 01:06:44,200
If I get as far as Algiers,
I'll give those fellas a run for their money.

652
01:06:44,283 --> 01:06:47,283
Africa is one continent I know
better than all their invisible men.

653
01:06:47,325 --> 01:06:50,158
- This the, uh, ooftish?
- That is the money, yes.

654
01:06:50,200 --> 01:06:52,242
If you don't mind,
we'll check the amount.

655
01:06:52,283 --> 01:06:54,325
<i>No, no.
I'll just take £500.</i>

656
01:06:54,367 --> 01:06:57,158
And, uh, Saul, you can instruct her
how to deposit it.

657
01:06:57,242 --> 01:06:59,908
<i>- Very good.
- I don't want it.</i>

658
01:06:59,950 --> 01:07:02,367
- I won't take it!
- Oh, yes, you will.

659
01:07:02,450 --> 01:07:04,908
I'm going to have my way
at least once with you.

660
01:07:04,992 --> 01:07:07,408
I wouldn't know
what to do with all that money.

661
01:07:07,492 --> 01:07:09,492
<i>- Mr. Farnsworthy will tell you.
- Yes.</i>

662
01:07:09,575 --> 01:07:11,575
I won't take it.
You'll want it.

663
01:07:11,658 --> 01:07:14,200
- Will you be Quiet?
- No.

664
01:07:14,283 --> 01:07:16,867
I can't stand a blubbering female.

665
01:07:16,908 --> 01:07:18,992
I've never seen
such a stubborn woman.

666
01:07:19,075 --> 01:07:22,367
And if you say one word of thanks,
I'll tear out your hair.

667
01:07:22,450 --> 01:07:25,242
Jerry, this isn't
paying you for anything.

668
01:07:25,325 --> 01:07:27,658
I can never do that.

669
01:07:27,700 --> 01:07:31,700
Come on now. Frown. Frown.

670
01:07:31,783 --> 01:07:35,158
You stubborn little monkey.
She won't do anything I ask her to.

671
01:07:35,242 --> 01:07:37,242
- Yes, yes.
- Jerry-

672
01:07:37,325 --> 01:07:39,908
The German embassy
telephoned here a few days ago.

673
01:07:39,950 --> 01:07:42,908
Their inquiry was pointedly casual.

674
01:07:42,992 --> 01:07:44,992
Anyone else ask for me?

675
01:07:45,075 --> 01:07:48,492
A friend of yours came in
to see me the other day...

676
01:07:48,575 --> 01:07:50,950
to consult me about
some inconceivable tangle...

677
01:07:50,992 --> 01:07:53,325
<i>under the Married Woman's
Property Act.</i>

678
01:07:53,408 --> 01:07:56,658
He was continually referring to you.

679
01:07:56,700 --> 01:07:59,617
Was he, uh, English?

680
01:07:59,658 --> 01:08:02,033
Too perfectly.

681
01:08:02,117 --> 01:08:05,367
Major Quive-Smith, he called himself.

682
01:08:08,992 --> 01:08:12,283
Anybody taking an interest in us, Peale?

683
01:08:12,367 --> 01:08:14,575
I've just been taking
a look outside, sir.

684
01:08:14,658 --> 01:08:17,325
The gentleman in the black hat
is still feeding the pigeons, sir.

685
01:08:17,408 --> 01:08:21,325
And now he's been joined by the military-looking
gentleman who visited you last week.

686
01:08:21,408 --> 01:08:24,700
Captain Thorndike's friend,
the gentleman with the monocle.

687
01:08:24,742 --> 01:08:27,492
- You see?
- Hmm.

688
01:08:27,575 --> 01:08:29,867
<i>- Thank you, Peale.
- Not at all, sir.</i>

689
01:08:32,283 --> 01:08:35,117
- Is there another way out of here?
- There's the back staircase.

690
01:08:35,158 --> 01:08:37,200
Oh, good.

691
01:08:38,783 --> 01:08:40,867
Thank you, Saul, very much.

692
01:08:40,908 --> 01:08:43,158
Good luck, you fool.

693
01:08:43,242 --> 01:08:46,825
Oh, uh, one thing more.

694
01:08:46,908 --> 01:08:49,908
If, at any time,
I am found...

695
01:08:49,992 --> 01:08:52,617
the coroner brings in
a verdict of suicide-

696
01:08:52,700 --> 01:08:56,700
- Suicide?
- Don't you believe it, huh?

697
01:08:56,742 --> 01:08:58,950
- But don't attempt to reopen the case.
- All Right.

698
01:08:58,992 --> 01:09:01,908
Bye, Jerry. You wait here for an hour
and go out the front way.

699
01:09:01,992 --> 01:09:04,992
- I'm going with you.
- Now see here. I've had enough of this.

700
01:09:05,075 --> 01:09:07,950
Don't you see that your own safety
lies in keeping away from me?

701
01:09:08,033 --> 01:09:10,867
- Where you goin'?
- To the Underground, on my way to nowhere.

702
01:09:10,950 --> 01:09:13,700
I'm goin' to the Underground too.
I gotta get home, haven't I?

703
01:09:13,700 --> 01:09:17,242
- Saul, will you drag this human leech off me?
- I will not.

704
01:09:17,325 --> 01:09:20,700
- I'm goin' to the Underground.
- All Right!

705
01:09:20,742 --> 01:09:23,867
- Good-bye.
- Bye.

706
01:09:23,950 --> 01:09:27,408
<i>It's all Right here. Read about It.</i>

707
01:09:27,492 --> 01:09:29,867
<i>First news out Right here!</i>

708
01:09:32,533 --> 01:09:36,533
<i>Right here!
First news out Right here. Read about It.</i>

709
01:09:36,617 --> 01:09:38,617
This is it, Jerry.

710
01:09:38,700 --> 01:09:42,158
And there's your ticket.
Good-bye, and take good care of yourself.

711
01:09:43,867 --> 01:09:46,700
You know, you're like
that little arrow on your hat-

712
01:09:46,783 --> 01:09:49,867
straight and shining- and that's
the way I'll always remember you.

713
01:09:52,533 --> 01:09:56,617
Good luck, little one.
Good-bye again.

714
01:09:56,700 --> 01:09:58,783
<i>Right here! First news out Right here!</i>

715
01:09:58,825 --> 01:10:01,242
Read about it!
Right here!

716
01:10:01,325 --> 01:10:03,283
First news out Right here!

717
01:10:06,450 --> 01:10:08,992
<i>Right here!</i>

718
01:10:09,075 --> 01:10:12,492
Come get your newspaper!

719
01:10:12,575 --> 01:10:15,117
<i>First results Right here!</i>

720
01:15:15,033 --> 01:15:18,242
Tube murder mystery! Paper!
Shocking murder mystery.

721
01:15:18,325 --> 01:15:20,492
Paper, sir?
Thank you, sir.

722
01:15:20,575 --> 01:15:24,700
Captain Thorndike's body was mangled
beyond recognition by the train.

723
01:15:24,742 --> 01:15:28,658
A positive identification was made
possible by his passport and wallet...

724
01:15:28,700 --> 01:15:30,700
which he carried.

725
01:15:30,783 --> 01:15:33,533
Shortly after the crime,
a ticket collector tried to stop a man...

726
01:15:33,575 --> 01:15:37,992
with a scar on his Right cheek who escaped
after presenting the wrong ticket.

727
01:15:38,075 --> 01:15:43,117
Evidently, the murderer had made
his way back through the tunnel on foot.

728
01:15:43,158 --> 01:15:46,117
Police are searching
for such a man. "

729
01:15:46,200 --> 01:15:49,200
- But who was killed?
- I don't know.

730
01:15:49,242 --> 01:15:51,867
Only a few people know,
and they won't tell.

731
01:15:51,950 --> 01:15:54,450
Hmm.

732
01:15:54,533 --> 01:15:57,992
Now they can hunt me down at leisure,
with the help of the British police.

733
01:16:00,283 --> 01:16:04,325
Perhaps I was a fool to come back here.
I could have been well out of London by now.

734
01:16:04,408 --> 01:16:06,783
But I wanted to hide out
till it was dark.

735
01:16:06,825 --> 01:16:09,783
Yeah. You're gonna stay here?

736
01:16:09,867 --> 01:16:12,242
Huh? No.

737
01:16:12,283 --> 01:16:15,533
<i>- I've got to get out tonight.
- Ain't I never gonna see you again?</i>

738
01:16:15,617 --> 01:16:19,325
<i>Of course. Someday
when this all blows over.</i>

739
01:16:20,867 --> 01:16:23,867
You know where my brother lives.

740
01:16:23,950 --> 01:16:26,742
Tell him I'm not dead.

741
01:16:26,825 --> 01:16:28,867
He'll take care of you.

742
01:16:28,908 --> 01:16:31,783
Ask him to write to me
in, oh, a fortnight.

743
01:16:31,825 --> 01:16:34,158
No. Three weeks.
Tell me all he can.

744
01:16:34,200 --> 01:16:38,075
By that time, I'll have a beard, and I can
walk into a village without being suspected.

745
01:16:38,158 --> 01:16:40,700
He needn't sign the letter
because I'll know whom it's from.

746
01:16:40,742 --> 01:16:43,575
- But if he puts your name on it-
- He won't.

747
01:16:43,658 --> 01:16:48,325
He'll address it to, uh-
to... your name.

748
01:16:48,408 --> 01:16:50,408
Mr. Stokes.

749
01:16:50,492 --> 01:16:52,867
Mr. Stokes, care of the post office
at Lyme Regis.

750
01:16:52,908 --> 01:16:55,992
- Lyme Regis.
- Uh, have you got a pencil? I'll write it down for you.

751
01:16:57,408 --> 01:17:01,200
Over there in the basket. Lyme Regis.

752
01:17:01,242 --> 01:17:04,117
Lyme Regis. That's it. Here now.

753
01:17:05,575 --> 01:17:09,533
Mr. D.F.- F" is for fool. "

754
01:17:09,617 --> 01:17:11,742
Stokes.

755
01:17:11,783 --> 01:17:13,825
Post office...

756
01:17:13,867 --> 01:17:18,575
Lyme Regis, Dorset.

757
01:17:18,658 --> 01:17:20,825
There you are. Now you can't forget.

758
01:17:20,908 --> 01:17:23,908
And remember: in three weeks.

759
01:17:23,992 --> 01:17:26,825
You got that?

760
01:17:26,867 --> 01:17:29,450
Well, come on now. Cheer up.

761
01:17:37,867 --> 01:17:41,367
You are the most stubborn little monkey
I have ever seen.

762
01:17:44,158 --> 01:17:47,867
But... this is as far as you go.

763
01:17:47,950 --> 01:17:49,992
Not a step further.

764
01:17:50,075 --> 01:17:52,950
Good-bye, Jerry, and thank you.

765
01:17:55,367 --> 01:17:57,367
Please go.

766
01:17:59,033 --> 01:18:02,742
- Kiss me.
- Jerry.

767
01:18:02,825 --> 01:18:04,867
Won't you kiss me?

768
01:18:04,950 --> 01:18:07,783
I know I'm never
gonna see you again!

769
01:18:07,825 --> 01:18:11,617
Why, dear, dear child.

770
01:18:18,033 --> 01:18:20,075
Alan.

771
01:18:33,533 --> 01:18:36,867
Come along, deary. There's a cozy
little pub just across the bridge.

772
01:18:36,908 --> 01:18:40,658
Ain't half bad either, ducky.
Come on.

773
01:18:40,700 --> 01:18:43,450
- What you want?
- Now, go on, miss. Go on.

774
01:18:43,492 --> 01:18:47,742
<i>I don't want to see you girls get Into trouble,
but you can't be pestering gentlemen.</i>

775
01:18:47,783 --> 01:18:50,783
- Who's pesterin' who?
- Now get along! Get along!

776
01:18:50,867 --> 01:18:53,908
I'm sorry, sir.
If I was you, I'd step along.

777
01:18:53,992 --> 01:18:56,200
Don't get mixed up
with these here girls.

778
01:18:56,283 --> 01:18:58,492
- Here, who you callin' names?
- Now that's enough!

779
01:18:58,533 --> 01:19:01,158
You leave the gentleman alone!
Get along. Get along.

780
01:19:01,242 --> 01:19:03,200
Good night, sir.

781
01:19:16,950 --> 01:19:19,158
Get going.
Get going.

782
01:20:04,700 --> 01:20:06,700
Fritz.

783
01:20:16,450 --> 01:20:18,658
Take me out of here, quick!

784
01:20:18,700 --> 01:20:20,867
- These here men!
- Come.

785
01:20:42,325 --> 01:20:45,033
Sit down, my dear.

786
01:20:45,075 --> 01:20:47,283
We're gonna have a little chat.

787
01:20:59,533 --> 01:21:02,367
Good afternoon, madam.
I think you may have a letter for me.

788
01:21:02,408 --> 01:21:04,700
- What name, please?
- Stokes.

789
01:21:08,617 --> 01:21:10,575
<i>- D.F. Stokes?
- Yes.</i>

790
01:21:12,908 --> 01:21:14,908
Come.
Go through them, please.

791
01:21:14,992 --> 01:21:17,742
Yes, sir. It's- It's in here.

792
01:21:20,658 --> 01:21:23,408
There's a parcel for you, too,
in the back room...

793
01:21:23,492 --> 01:21:25,825
if you'll wait a minute, please.

794
01:21:25,908 --> 01:21:27,908
Just a minute.

795
01:21:29,742 --> 01:21:32,575
<i>Mary.</i>

796
01:23:46,825 --> 01:23:48,867
<i>Thorndike.</i>

797
01:23:58,033 --> 01:24:00,075
<i>Thorndike!</i>

798
01:24:02,700 --> 01:24:05,825
You might as well be reasonable,
my dear fellow.

799
01:24:05,867 --> 01:24:10,242
I'm so glad you had the sense not to
break out while I was sealing you up.

800
01:24:10,325 --> 01:24:13,950
- Now you cannot get out.
- You can't get in, you mean.

801
01:24:14,033 --> 01:24:17,992
I have no desire to enter a cave
after a trapped animal...

802
01:24:18,075 --> 01:24:20,700
even though I know
you have no weapons.

803
01:24:20,742 --> 01:24:23,658
I admired your stone door
so much that I imitated it...

804
01:24:23,700 --> 01:24:26,450
by wedging another stone
on the outside.

805
01:24:26,533 --> 01:24:28,867
You're sealed up, as in a grave.

806
01:24:55,783 --> 01:24:59,367
It's no use, Thorndike.
No use at all.

807
01:25:04,075 --> 01:25:06,450
Couldn't you have given me
a cleaner death than this?

808
01:25:06,533 --> 01:25:09,158
<i>Don't be a fool.
I could have killed you an hour ago.</i>

809
01:25:09,242 --> 01:25:11,617
<i>My purpose was to trap you alive.</i>

810
01:25:11,700 --> 01:25:14,492
<i>You've been Immensely helpful.</i>

811
01:25:22,367 --> 01:25:25,617
<i>- What is it you want?
- Now you're being sensible.</i>

812
01:25:28,283 --> 01:25:30,408
<i>- Have you got It?
- What Is It?</i>

813
01:25:30,492 --> 01:25:33,033
<i>It Is the confession that,
with the approval of your government...</i>

814
01:25:33,117 --> 01:25:35,117
<i>you sought to assassinate
our führer.</i>

815
01:25:35,200 --> 01:25:37,200
Go to the devil!

816
01:25:37,283 --> 01:25:40,867
You're growing wearisome, Thorndike.

817
01:25:42,492 --> 01:25:44,492
Once more, I ask you to sign...

818
01:25:44,575 --> 01:25:46,742
<i>and save us both
an unpleasant conclusion.</i>

819
01:25:46,825 --> 01:25:49,367
I told you once, I don't sign lies!

820
01:25:49,450 --> 01:25:53,283
<i>You also told me you no longer believed
In killing, yet you killed one of my men.</i>

821
01:25:53,367 --> 01:25:55,742
Oh, I'm not blaming you in the least.

822
01:25:55,783 --> 01:25:59,742
I merely wish to point out
that a lie is relative...

823
01:25:59,783 --> 01:26:01,825
<i>as Is truth.</i>

824
01:26:01,867 --> 01:26:05,825
I tell you, I did not intend
to shoot your bloody führer!

825
01:26:08,450 --> 01:26:10,867
I believe you.
I believe you're sincere.

826
01:26:10,950 --> 01:26:13,242
I really do at last.

827
01:26:13,283 --> 01:26:15,742
You actually think you had
no intention to kill...

828
01:26:15,825 --> 01:26:19,283
<i>that It was all a sporting stalk, "
as you call It.</i>

829
01:26:19,325 --> 01:26:22,783
- It was!
- And yet every minute, you were deceiving yourself.

830
01:26:22,867 --> 01:26:26,200
- And every hour since then, you have lied to yourself.
- No!

831
01:26:26,242 --> 01:26:29,158
<i>You've refused to face
your secret self, Thorndike.</i>

832
01:26:29,242 --> 01:26:33,283
<i>From the moment you crossed the frontier,
you became an unconscious assassin.</i>

833
01:26:36,158 --> 01:26:39,617
I'm going to show you to yourself
as you really are, Thorndike.

834
01:26:39,658 --> 01:26:43,242
I'm going to break through that
civilized English mask you were born with.

835
01:26:43,325 --> 01:26:46,492
I'm going to show you
what you really are and were-

836
01:26:46,533 --> 01:26:48,992
<i>an assassin.</i>

837
01:26:49,075 --> 01:26:52,408
You fool!
You fanatical fool!

838
01:26:58,200 --> 01:27:00,158
<i>A token for you, Thorndike.</i>

839
01:27:02,533 --> 01:27:04,783
<i>To make you see the truth.</i>

840
01:27:08,617 --> 01:27:11,033
Jerry. Jerry.

841
01:27:13,700 --> 01:27:16,283
Where is she?
What have you done with her?

842
01:27:18,533 --> 01:27:21,325
Do you expect me
to lie to you, Thorndike?

843
01:27:21,408 --> 01:27:25,075
Do you expect me to tell you
that it was a sporting stalk?

844
01:27:25,117 --> 01:27:27,117
<i>No.</i>

845
01:27:27,200 --> 01:27:30,533
<i>I am honest with you
as you are not honest with me.</i>

846
01:27:30,575 --> 01:27:32,575
<i>She made your mistake, Thorndike.</i>

847
01:27:32,658 --> 01:27:34,742
<i>She flaunted obvious power.</i>

848
01:27:34,825 --> 01:27:36,783
<i>She refused to tell us anything.</i>

849
01:27:39,200 --> 01:27:42,783
Do you know that if it hadn't been for that
postal address you so thoughtfully wrote down...

850
01:27:42,825 --> 01:27:45,117
<i>I don't know what
I should have done.</i>

851
01:27:45,200 --> 01:27:48,533
If you've harmed that girl,
I swear I'll kill you somehow!

852
01:27:48,617 --> 01:27:51,533
I'll live to kill you
if it's the last thing I do!

853
01:27:51,617 --> 01:27:56,408
You believed that the death of our sacred
führer would be no great loss to the world.

854
01:27:56,492 --> 01:28:01,325
<i>Surely, then, the death of a girl like that
would be no loss at all.</i>

855
01:28:01,408 --> 01:28:04,783
She was found dead
in the street, Thorndike.

856
01:28:04,867 --> 01:28:07,742
The police reported that she, uh...

857
01:28:07,825 --> 01:28:10,450
jumped to her death from a Window.

858
01:28:10,575 --> 01:28:14,075
She had nothing to do with my actions!
She was innocent! Innocent!

859
01:28:14,158 --> 01:28:17,450
Yes, just as innocent as our führer
was of any wrongdoing against you.

860
01:28:17,533 --> 01:28:21,075
No! He's guilty- guilty against me
and against humanity!

861
01:28:21,158 --> 01:28:23,742
Against every decent,
peaceful person in the world!

862
01:28:23,825 --> 01:28:26,242
He's guilty of hatred,
intolerance and murder!

863
01:28:26,325 --> 01:28:29,533
<i>- And that Is why you tried to kill him?
- Yes, I intended to shoot!</i>

864
01:28:29,575 --> 01:28:32,450
I didn't know what I was doing!
I didn't realize my purpose!

865
01:28:32,492 --> 01:28:35,200
I wouldn't face the fact
that I can make myself the instrument...

866
01:28:35,283 --> 01:28:37,867
of all the pitiable, oppressed,
suffering people of the world!

867
01:28:37,950 --> 01:28:40,658
I wonder why I put that shell in my gun.
Now I know!

868
01:28:40,700 --> 01:28:45,200
Yes, I intended to kill! I intended to
avenge the crimes of this monstrous tyrant!

869
01:28:45,242 --> 01:28:47,825
<i>- I know it now!
- And you were acting for your government?</i>

870
01:28:47,908 --> 01:28:50,950
<i>- No, for myself!.
- But It was for the sake of your country, wasn't It?</i>

871
01:28:50,992 --> 01:28:54,533
No, for mine, as well as others.
For your misguided people as well as my own!

872
01:28:54,617 --> 01:28:57,867
<i>Then even though your government knew
nothing about you, you were acting on their behalf.</i>

873
01:28:57,950 --> 01:29:00,908
<i>- No!
- You said you wouldn't sign lies. I've proved them true.</i>

874
01:29:00,992 --> 01:29:05,158
<i>You've admitted the whole thing.</i>

875
01:29:06,658 --> 01:29:08,867
I have a plane
waiting for me in Croydon.

876
01:29:08,908 --> 01:29:13,117
I must soon go. But when I go, it will be
with that document, signed by yourself.

877
01:29:13,200 --> 01:29:16,242
It may interest you to know
why that document is needed.

878
01:29:16,283 --> 01:29:21,283
It will make interesting reading when
we publish the First German white paper.

879
01:29:21,367 --> 01:29:23,367
What do you mean?

880
01:29:23,450 --> 01:29:27,158
<i>- My country has already marched Into Poland.
- I don't believe you.</i>

881
01:29:27,242 --> 01:29:29,450
Twenty divisions
crossed the frontier today.

882
01:29:29,533 --> 01:29:33,200
<i>If you're telling the truth, England
and France will be at war with you within a week!</i>

883
01:29:33,283 --> 01:29:35,325
You're commencing to rave.

884
01:29:35,408 --> 01:29:40,408
We shall take Poland, and no nation
in Europe will dare to raise a hand.

885
01:29:40,492 --> 01:29:44,325
We're on the march at last, Thorndike.

886
01:29:44,408 --> 01:29:46,408
Today, Europe.

887
01:29:46,492 --> 01:29:48,617
Tomorrow, the world.

888
01:29:59,408 --> 01:30:02,492
<i>Thorndike.</i>

889
01:30:02,575 --> 01:30:05,033
<i>Thorndike, why don't you answer me?</i>

890
01:30:05,075 --> 01:30:07,117
Uh, what?

891
01:30:07,158 --> 01:30:09,908
<i>I'm waiting for you to sign.</i>

892
01:30:09,992 --> 01:30:14,700
Uh- I've- I've got
to read it, haven't I?

893
01:30:14,783 --> 01:30:17,283
<i>Oh, Certainly.
Take your time.</i>

894
01:30:34,617 --> 01:30:37,617
<i>- Have you got a cigarette?
- Yes. Certainly.</i>

895
01:30:42,617 --> 01:30:44,783
<i>It's on the stick.
Pull It In.</i>

896
01:30:56,783 --> 01:30:58,742
<i>Have you read It?</i>

897
01:30:59,867 --> 01:31:02,533
I've got to think it over.

898
01:31:04,700 --> 01:31:07,075
I shall give you
15 minutes, Thorndike.

899
01:31:11,783 --> 01:31:15,908
<i>When the time Is up, If you haven't
delivered that document to me properly signed...</i>

900
01:31:15,950 --> 01:31:18,992
<i>I shall shut off your air
and go on my way.</i>

901
01:31:19,075 --> 01:31:21,450
<i>You may last a few hours...</i>

902
01:31:21,533 --> 01:31:25,200
<i>but they will be most unpleasant.</i>

903
01:31:25,242 --> 01:31:28,200
How do I know you'll let me out
after I've signed?

904
01:31:30,075 --> 01:31:32,575
I shall remove the outside stone...

905
01:31:32,617 --> 01:31:35,533
when you're ready to hand it out.

906
01:31:35,617 --> 01:31:38,200
<i>And then shoot me when I crawl out.</i>

907
01:31:39,408 --> 01:31:41,575
My gun is in its holster.

908
01:31:41,658 --> 01:31:45,575
<i>You will have to take my word
as a fellow hunter for that.</i>

909
01:31:46,992 --> 01:31:49,283
<i>Thirteen minutes, Thorndike.</i>

910
01:32:24,742 --> 01:32:26,742
I've removed the barrier, Thorndike.

911
01:32:26,825 --> 01:32:28,825
<i>Are you ready?</i>

912
01:32:31,367 --> 01:32:34,283
<i>- Do you hear me, Thorndike?
- Yes, I hear you.</i>

913
01:32:34,367 --> 01:32:37,033
<i>Five minutes more.</i>

914
01:32:37,117 --> 01:32:39,450
Have you removed the outside stone?

915
01:32:39,533 --> 01:32:42,533
<i>Open your side of the cave,
and you'll see.</i>

916
01:32:57,992 --> 01:33:01,158
<i>- Are you satisfied?
- Yes, I can see it's clear.</i>

917
01:33:04,533 --> 01:33:06,658
Your time is nearly up, Thorndike.

918
01:33:06,700 --> 01:33:08,700
Hand out the document.

919
01:33:08,783 --> 01:33:12,492
You'll have to reach for it.

920
01:33:12,575 --> 01:33:15,158
Hand it out through the venthole.

921
01:33:20,992 --> 01:33:23,200
<i>Your time Is up.
I'm waiting.</i>

922
01:33:23,283 --> 01:33:25,950
<i>And be sure It's signed.</i>

923
01:33:42,200 --> 01:33:44,867
<i>There It Is.</i>

924
01:33:44,950 --> 01:33:46,950
Push it nearer.

925
01:33:47,033 --> 01:33:49,783
I don't propose
to have my wrist seized.

926
01:33:54,783 --> 01:33:57,408
You can come out now, Thorndike.

927
01:34:00,700 --> 01:34:04,492
Come on out, Thorndike.
You're free at last.

928
01:35:44,575 --> 01:35:47,867
You're like that little arrow on your hat-
straight and shining-

929
01:35:47,950 --> 01:35:50,575
and that's the way
I'll always remember you.

930
01:35:55,367 --> 01:35:59,492
<i>Surely then the death of
a girl like that would be no loss at all.</i>

931
01:35:59,575 --> 01:36:03,117
Ain't-Ain't I never gonna see you again?

932
01:36:04,700 --> 01:36:07,408
Every good soldier
needs a crest for his hat.

933
01:36:15,783 --> 01:36:18,783
<i>- Your course and objective
are clearly marked on this map.</i>

934
01:36:18,867 --> 01:36:20,825
- Yes, sir.
- Here.

935
01:36:20,908 --> 01:36:23,033
You will make your reconnaissance
and return immediately.

936
01:36:23,117 --> 01:36:25,742
<i>- Right, sir.
- All the best, old chap.</i>

937
01:36:25,825 --> 01:36:27,825
Thank you, sir.

938
01:37:00,075 --> 01:37:02,492
We've just passed over into Germany.

939
01:37:02,575 --> 01:37:05,242
Right.

940
01:37:05,325 --> 01:37:07,617
- One of the men just bailed out!
- What? Who?

941
01:37:07,658 --> 01:37:09,575
- Thorndike.
- Thorndike?

942
01:37:14,992 --> 01:37:18,575
<i>And from now on, somewhere within Germany...</i>

943
01:37:18,658 --> 01:37:21,700
<i>Is a man with a precision rifle...</i>

944
01:37:21,783 --> 01:37:26,242
<i>and the High degree of Intelligence
and training that Is required to use It.</i>

945
01:37:27,492 --> 01:37:30,658
<i>It may be days, months...</i>

946
01:37:30,700 --> 01:37:32,700
<i>or even years...</i>

947
01:37:32,742 --> 01:37:35,908
<i>but this time
he clearly knows his purpose...</i>

948
01:37:35,950 --> 01:37:39,242
<i>and, unflinching, faces his destiny.</i>
